The ECB surprise: when a few tenths of a point change the residential market

Over the past few months, many European buyers had begun to assume that the most aggressive stage of monetary tightening had been left behind. However, the European Central Bank's latest move has once again altered the market's expectations.

The rise in interest rates to 2.25% has triggered an immediate reaction in the financial markets and, especially, in the Euribor, the main reference index for millions of mortgages in the eurozone. What for some may seem like a technical adjustment of barely a few tenths of a point, for thousands of families means a significant reduction in their borrowing capacity and a direct increase in the cost of accessing housing.

The concern does not arise solely from the increase in mortgage instalments. The real impact lies in the cumulative effect that higher financing costs generate in a residential market that was already dragging structural problems of insufficient supply, high prices and a growing difficulty in accessing housing in the main European cities.

Markets such as Madrid, Barcelona, Paris, Milan, Berlin or Amsterdam could experience a summer marked by lower mortgage activity, as many potential buyers will have to review their budgets or postpone purchase decisions in the face of less favourable financial conditions.

The feeling that is beginning to spread among buyers and investors is clear: the cost of money is once again becoming one of the most decisive factors in the evolution of the European residential market.

Less buying capacity, fewer mortgages and a more selective market

The impact of the rate hike is quickly transferred to the daily life of those seeking financing.

With a higher Euribor, financial institutions adjust their risk criteria and reduce the maximum amount they are willing to lend for the same level of income. This means that many buyers will be able to access lower-value homes or will have to contribute a higher percentage of initial savings to complete the operation.

In practical terms, a family that just a few months ago could finance a home of a certain value may now discover that its purchasing capacity has been considerably reduced, even while maintaining exactly the same salary level.

